            <p>370 W. 33<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> St.<lb/>
                New York. 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> May 1884.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have received a circular<lb/> from a committee of the H.E. Society&#44; ap&#45;<lb/>pealing for aid on behalf of the educa&#45;<lb/>tion of the children of the Jewish refugees<lb/>colonized in your city. Desiring to respond<lb/> thereto&#44; if the cause of Judaism&#8212;consequently<lb/> that of humanity&#8212;would be promoted<lb/> thereby&#44; I take the liberty of handing you<lb/> herewith&#44; an envelope containing a small<lb/> donation&#44; requesting of you to do me the favor<lb/> of forwarding it to its address&#44; if the school is<lb/> under such religious influence as you approve<lb/> of. Otherwise please return it to me&#44; and nothing<lb/> need or will be said about it.&#95;&#95;Kindly excuse my<lb/> encroachment&#44; and oblige Yours truly<lb/></p>
            <p>David M. P&#239;za<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
